    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Angelica sinensis improperly include triggering allergic reactions, particularly in individuals with sensitivities to plants in the same family, such as the carrot and parsley family. Additionally, consuming large quantities of Angelica sinensis may cause a significant drop in blood pressure, potentially leading to dizziness, fainting, or other cardiovascular issues. Prolonged or excessive use of Angelica sinensis has been linked to liver damage, as it contains compounds that can be toxic to the liver in high concentrations. Furthermore, Angelica sinensis may interact with certain medications, including blood thinners such as warfarin, as well as other herbs and supplements, potentially increasing the risk of bleeding or other adverse effects. This is due to the plant's ability to enhance the activity of certain enzymes that metabolize these medications."
